Binding of muonated hydrogen molecules on the occasionof the Born-Oppenheimer approximation 90th anniversary.Results

In order to describe two interacting hydrogen atoms, we replace, in the Hamiltonian, the muon mass µ by 1, and in order to describe two interacting di-muonated hydrogen atoms, we replace the electron mass, equal to 1, by the muon mass µ. Following a procedure similar to the one described elsewhere [6,7], we obtain in the former case:

• Binding energy of two hydrogen atoms: −0.125949 a.u.;

• If 1.626 < c < 1.627, the energy of the hydrogen molecule is: −0.936496 a.u.;

• If c → ∞, the energy of the hydrogen molecule approaches −0.810547 a.u.;

• Distance between the centres in the hydrogen molecule: 1.626 a.u.;

• Radius of the electron orbit in the atoms of the hydrogen molecule: 1.50 a.u.;

• Radius of the proton orbit in the atoms of the hydrogen molecule: 0.229 a.u.;

The results so obtained are graphically summarized in Figure 1. Similarly, for two interacting muonic hydrogen atoms, we replace in the Hamiltonian the electron rest mass (1 a.u.) by the muon mass µ, yielding:

• Binding energy of two muonic hydrogen atoms: −7.6337 a.u.;

• If 0.0142 < c < 0.0143, the energy of the di-muonic hydrogen molecule is: −106.059 a.u.;

• If c → ∞, the energy of the di-muonic hydrogen molecule approaches −98.4153 a.u.;

• Distance between the centres in the muonic hydrogen molecule: 0.0142 a.u.;

• Radius of the muon orbit in the atoms of the muonic hydrogen molecule: 0.0112 a.u.;

• Radius of the proton orbit in the atoms of the muonic hydrogen molecule: 0.0065 a.u.;

